{"title_page": "Joachim Kunert", "text_new": "{{short description|German film director}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image =\n| name        = Joachim Kunert\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1929|9|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Berlin]], Germany\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation  = Film director, screenwriter\n| yearsactive = 1954-1989\n}}\n\n'''Joachim Kunert''' (born 24 September 1929) is a German [[film director]] and [[screenwriter]]. He has directed more than 20 films since 1954. His 1965 film ''[[The Adventures of Werner Holt (film)|The Adventures of Werner Holt]]'' was entered into the [[4th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Moscow1965\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1965 |title=4th Moscow International Film Festival (1965) |accessdate=2012-12-06 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116145645/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1965 |archivedate=16 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[Ein Strom flie\u00dft durch Deutschland]]'' (1954)\n* ''[[Die Dresdner Philharmoniker]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[Besondere Kennzeichen: keine]]'' (1956)\n* ''[[Tatort Berlin]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[Der Lotterieschwede]]'' (1958)\n* ''[[Ehesache Lorenz]]'' (1959)\n* ''[[Seilergasse 8]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[The Second Track]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[The Adventures of Werner Holt (film)|The Adventures of Werner Holt]]'' (1965)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0475105|Joachim Kunert}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kunert, Joachim}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German film directors]]\n[[Category:German television directors]]\n[[Category:German screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Writers from Berlin]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Berlin]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:Male screenwriters]]\n\n\n{{Germany-film-director-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German film director}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image =\n| name        = Joachim Kunert\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1929|9|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Berlin]], Germany\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation  = Film director, screenwriter\n| yearsactive = 1954-1989\n}}\n\n'''Joachim Kunert''' (born 24 September 1929) is a German [[film director]] and [[screenwriter]]. He has directed more than 20 films since 1954. His 1965 film ''[[The Adventures of Werner Holt (film)|The Adventures of Werner Holt]]'' was entered into the [[4th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Moscow1965\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1965 |title=4th Moscow International Film Festival (1965) |accessdate=2012-12-06 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116145645/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1965 |archivedate=16 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[Die Dresdner Philharmoniker]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[The Adventures of Werner Holt (film)|The Adventures of Werner Holt]]'' (1965)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0475105|Joachim Kunert}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kunert, Joachim}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German film directors]]\n[[Category:German screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Writers from Berlin]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Berlin]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:Male screenwriters]]\n\n\n{{Germany-film-director-stub}}\n", "name_user": "91.3.204.232", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSelected filmography)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joachim_Kunert"}
{"title_page": "Percivall Pott", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2019}}\n{{For|the Member of Parliament for Devizes|Percivall Pott (politician)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:PercivallPottb026992.JPG|thumb|Percivall Pott, engraved from an original picture by [[Nathaniel Dance-Holland]], [[National Library of Medicine]], Images from the History of Medicine.]]\n\n''' Percivall Pott''' (6 January 1714 in London \u2013 22 December 1788) was an English surgeon, one of the founders of [[orthopaedics]], and the first scientist to demonstrate that a cancer may be caused by an environmental [[carcinogen]].\n\n==Career==\nHe served his apprenticeship with Edward Nourse, assistant surgeon to [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], and in 1736 was admitted to the [[Barbers' Company]] and licensed to practice. He became assistant surgeon to St Bartholomew's in 1744 and full surgeon from 1749 till 1787.\n\nAs the first surgeon of his day in England, excelling even his pupil, [[Casey Linton (surgeon)|John Hunter]], on the practical side, Pott introduced various important innovations in procedure, doing much to abolish the extensive use of [[eschar]]otics and the [[cautery]] that was prevalent when he began his career.\n\nIn 1756, Pott sustained a broken leg after a fall from his horse.  It is often assumed that his injury was the same one that later came to be known as [[Pott's fracture]], but in reality Pott's broken leg was a much more serious compound fracture of the [[tibia]]. As he lay in the muck, he sent a servant to buy a door from a nearby construction site, then had himself placed on the door and taken home. Surgeons cleaned the wound and discussed amputation, an operation which at the time had a very high rate of failure, as it often led to sepsis and death, but Pott prevailed on them to splint the leg, and he ultimately recovered completely.<ref>Gordon 1994, pp. 126\u2013127</ref> In 1769 Pott published ''Some Few Remarks upon Fractures and Dislocations''.  The book was translated into French and Italian, and had a far-reaching influence in Britain and France.   His name was written in the annals of medicine, by first describing arthritic [[tuberculosis]] of the [[vertebral column|spine]] ([[Pott's disease]]).  He gave an excellent clinical description in his ''Remarks on that Kind of Palsy of the Lower Limbs''.  Among his other writings the most noteworthy are ''A Treatise on Ruptures'' (1756), and ''Chirurgical Observations''.\n\nIn 1775, Pott found an association between exposure to [[soot]] and a high incidence of scrotal cancer (later found to be a type of [[squamous cell carcinoma]]) in [[chimney sweep]]s. This unusual disease, later termed [[chimney sweeps' carcinoma]] due to Pott's investigation, was the first [[occupational disease|occupational]] link to cancer, and Pott became the first person to associate a malignancy with an environmental [[carcinogen]], implicating chimney soot as a direct contact carcinogen to skin.  His work helped lead to the [[Chimney Sweepers Act 1788]].\n\nLatter animal studies (1933) painting coal tar onto skin would demonstrate the role of the first proven chemical carcinogen [[benzo(a)pyrene]], which occurs in high concentrations in smoke and chimney soot, with the process that Pott first identified. Pott's early investigations thus contributed to the science of [[epidemiology]] and the [[Chimney Sweepers Act 1788]].<ref>Gordon 1994, p. 128</ref> The same chemical responsible for Pott's unique cancer of chimney sweeps has since proven to be a prime suspect in various cancers caused by cigarette smoke.\n\nIn 1765, he was elected Master of the Company of Surgeons, the forerunner of the [[Royal College of Surgeons of England]].\n\nA manuscript copy of his 1779 lectures on surgery survive as part of the Manchester Medical Manuscripts Collection held by special collections at the University of Manchester Library with the reference MMM/15/2/6.\n\n== Late career ==\n\nPercivall Potts married in 1740. They lived together in [[Lisle's Tennis Court|Lincoln's Inn Fields]] in London and would go on to have five sons and four daughters.<ref name=\":02\">Classics in oncology. Sir Percivall Pott (1714\u20131788). ''CA: a cancer journal for clinicians'' '''24''', 108\u2013116 (1974).</ref>\n\nAlthough little more is known about Percivall Pott's private life, Pott is regularly described as having excellent character, and an archetypical English surgeon. It is believed that Pott's standard of living was a contributor to the rise of the surgeon within social standings.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nAmid the patient wards, Pott also honed his writing skills and believed in patient education.<ref name=\":2\" /> He would distribute pamphlets, noting his observations and thoughts on topics ranging from \"[[Head injury|head injuries]], [[hydrocele]], [[fistula]], rupture, and fracture\", in the hospital environment.<ref name=\":02\" /> These pamphlets were in high demand and would sell for more than one shilling and six pence. Between 1760s and the 1770s over fourteen of Pott's pamphlets were in circulation.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nPercivall Pott's dedication to his patients and standard of care garnered Pott high praise and fame. He is generally regarded as one of the two greatest surgeons of the 18th century along with his student John Hunter.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 1786, he was honoured as the first Honorary Fellow of the [[Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh]].<ref name=\":02\" /> Shortly after, he retired in 1787 and was named a governor of [[St Bartholomew's Hospital|St. Bartholomew's Hospital]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Chimney sweepers' carcinoma ==\n\nPercivall Pott has influenced medicine and modern understanding of diseases. Many diseases today are his namesake including: [[Pott's fracture]], [[Pott disease|Pott's disease]] of the spine, and [[Pott's puffy tumor]]. One disease which does not, yet is important to Pott's legacy is chimney sweeper's carcinoma. Pott quickly recognised the association between carcinoma and [[chimney sweep]]s and published his findings in a piece titled \"Chirurgical Observations relative to\u2026the cancer of the scrotum.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> He wrote that the disease was, \" peculiar to a certain sort of people [ and ] which has not at least to my knowledge, been publicly noticed \u2013 I mean the chimney-sweepers \u2019 cancer. The disease, in these people, seems to derive its origin from a lodgment of soot in the rugae of the scrotum.\"<ref name=\":0\">Pott, Percivall. ''[Chirurgical Observations] : Containing I. Observations Relative to the Cataract, Ii. Some Few Remarks, on the Polypus of the Nose, Iii. Observations on the Cancer of the Scrotum, Iv. Observations and Cases Relative to the Different Kinds of Ruptures, V. Observations on the Mortification of the Toes and Feet.'' Printed for Hawes, W. Clarke, and R. Collins ... 1775. ''Chirurgical Works of Percivall Pott'', vol. 5.</ref>\n[[File:The chirurgical works of Percivall Pott (1808) (14769597084).jpg|thumb|Diagram from the chirurgical works of Percivall Pott]]\n\n=== Discovery and identification credit ===\n\nScrotal cancer, although largely thought to have been identified by Percival Pott, had been thought to have been described nearly 40 years before Pott's \"Chirurgical Observations\" as a \"canker of privities\" per documentation in the burial records of the Parish of [[St Botolph without Aldgate|St. Botolph without Aldgate]] from 1589 to 1599.<ref>Forbes, Thomas Rogers. ''Chronicle from Aldgate; Life and Death in Shakespeare's London.'' Yale University Press, 1971.{{page needed|date=March 2017}}</ref> These descriptions are ambiguous and it is unclear which anatomical parts considered \"privities\". As such, most historians generally agree that Bassius first correctly described scrotal cancer in 1731.<ref name=\":2\" /> Some historians argue that what Bassius considered scrotal cancer was in fact perineal abscesses to the scrotum as opposed to carcinoma. The minority of historians who agree with this fact, attribute the discovery of scrotal cancer to Treyling in 1740.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal |pmid=4922857 |pmc=1069432 |year=1970 |author1=Kipling |first1=M. D. |title=A monstrous growth: An historical note on carcinoma of the scrotum |journal=British Journal of Industrial Medicine |volume=27 |issue=4 |pages=382\u20134 |last2=Usherwood |first2=R |last3=Varley |first3=R |doi=10.1136/oem.27.4.382}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/oem.32.3.244 |pmid=1098690 |pmc=1008067 |title=Percivall Pott and cancer scroti |journal=Occupational and Environmental Medicine |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=244\u20136 |year=1975 |last1=Kipling |first1=M D |last2=Waldron |first2=H A }}</ref>\n\n=== Surgery ===\n\nAs a surgeon, Pott was well respected and often assisted fellow surgeons. Pott was viewed as a mentor and even allowed other physicians and surgeons to live with him while under his guidance.<ref name=\":02\" /> Despite the surgical trends of his time, Pott did not agree with severe treatments and [[heroic medicine]] but rather preferred gentler forms. Percivall Pott's son-in-law, [[James Earle]], described Pott's surgery as being \"divested of great part of its horrors, became, comparatively, a pleasing study.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Soot and occupational cancer ===\n\nIn addition to surgery, Pott's focused on [[public health]] as well drawing his attention to the challenges of chimney-sweeps in his community. He wrote, \"in their early infancy, they are most frequently treated with great brutality, and almost starved with cold and hunger; they are thrust up narrow, and sometimes hot chimneys, where they are bruised, burned and almost suffocated; and when they get to puberty, become peculiarly liable to a most noisome, painful, and fatal disease.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Pott's approach was unique amongst his contemporaries in that he did not simply note an association but approached [[chimney sweeps' carcinoma]] from a causal perspective. His work helped later identify soot as the disease-causing agent.<ref name=\":2\" /> Pott did not figure this out on his own, but rather pointed research in the right direction. During Pott's time, there were many discussions pertaining to the cause of scrotal cancer. [[James Earle]] believed that the cancer was caused as a result of the soot entering and residing in the rugae of the scrotum. He famously argued this point based on a trend seen where gardeners who used soot to kill slugs had developed skin carcinoma on their hands. In 1878, George Lawson suggested that the cancer was caused by the friction generated by chimney sweeper's overalls against the scrotum while sifting though soot. This idea was explored by Passey in 1992 who demonstrated that it was the ethereal extract of soot which was capable of inducing sarcoma.<ref name=\":1\" /> Furthermore, Pott also identified that prepubescent boys were most vulnerable to the [[carcinoma]].<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1464-410X.2011.10487.x |pmid=21794063 |title=Percivall Pott, the Environment and Cancer |journnfkgn rg fbv bgfg bgbal=BJU International |volume=108 |issue=4 |pages=479\u201381 |year=2011 |last1=Herr |first1=Harry W. }}</ref> Pott rose to fame for these connections between occupational hazards and cancer malignancy even though the connection was not fully understood at the time. Pott's \"Chirurgical Observations\" provided a framework to shape the modern understanding of ''[[Occupational cancer]]s.''\n\n== Influence ==\n\nPercivall Pott's work influenced a wave of researcher and change in public policies. After his initial publication, more clinical cases began to emerge rapidly over the following years.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1056/NEJM191011241632103 |title=Cancer of the Scrotum |journal=The Boston Medical and Surgical Journal |volume=163 |issue=21 |pages=792\u20137 |year=1910 |last1=Green |first1=Robert M. }}</ref> This triggered a series of \"[[Chimney Sweepers Act 1788|Chimney Sweepers' Acts]]\" which aimed to protect chimney sweepers. These facilitated the formation of societies like the \"Society for Superseding the Necessity of Climbing Boys, by Encouraging a New Method of Sweeping Chimneys and for Improving the Condition of Children and Others Employed by Chimney Sweepers\" in 1803 which included the likes of [[Duke]]s, [[Earl]]s, and [[Patronage|Royal Patrons]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDespite outcry and public demands to change chimney sweeping practices, such as suggesting that young chimney sweeping boys be replaced with mechanical devices, insurance companies, and homeowners argued that Chimney Sweeper's carcinoma was a small price to pay for the protection of the mass population against smoke and chimney fires.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=17309190 |year=2006 |author1=Androutsos |first1=G |title=The outstanding British surgeon Percivall Pott (1714\u20131789) and the first description of an occupational cancer |journal=Journal of the Balkan Union of Oncology |volume=11 |issue=4 |pages=533\u20139 }}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> Despite the call for action as early as 1788, Pott's work finally began to influence change in 1875, when a decline in scrotal cancer incidence and mortality was noted.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite journal |pmid=13396156 |pmc=1037746 |year=1957 |author1=Brown |first1=J. R. |title=Percivall Pott (1714\u20131788) and chimney sweepers' cancer of the scrotum |journal=British Journal of Industrial Medicine |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=68\u201370 |last2=Thornton |first2=J. L. |doi=10.1136/oem.14.1.68}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cancer cluster]]\n* [[History of medicine]]\n* [[History of surgery]]\n* [[Pott disease]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Gordon \n  | first = Richard |authorlink=Richard Gordon (English author)\n  | title = The Alarming History of Medicine \n  | publisher=St Martin's Press \n  | location = New York \n  | year = 1994 \n  | isbn = 0-312-10411-1 \n  | url = https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Alarming_History_of_Medicine.html?id=IbCX2qYzf-gC\n}}\n* Dobson, J., 'Percivall Pott' in ''Annals of the Royal College of Surgeons of England'', vol. 50 (1972), pp.&nbsp;54\u201365\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Pott, Percivall}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070119173938/http://www.surgeons.org.uk/history-of-surgeons/percival-pott.html History of Surgeons \u2013 Percivall Pott]. surgeons.org.uk England\n* [http://www.whonamedit.com/doctor.cfm/1103.html Article on Percivall Pott] in [[Who Named It]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120716224020/http://www.surgical-tutor.org.uk/default-home.htm?surgeons%2Fpott.htm~right Sir Percivall Pott]. Surgical Tutor UK.\n\n----\n{{EB1911|wstitle=Pott, Percivall|volume=22|pages=210\u2013211}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pott, Percivall}}\n[[Category:1714 births]]\n[[Category:1788 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:English surgeons]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Medical College of St Bartholomew's Hospital]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2019}}\n{{For|the Member of Parliament for Devizes|Percivall Pott (politician)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:PercivallPottb026992.JPG|thumb|Percivall Pott, engraved from an original picture by [[Nathaniel Dance-Holland]], [[National Library of Medicine]], Images from the History of Medicine.]]\n\n''' Percivall Pott''' (6 January 1714 in London \u2013 22 December 1788) was an English surgeon, one of the founders of [[orthopaedics]], and the first scientist to demonstrate that a cancer may be caused by an environmental [[carcinogen]].\n\n==Career==\nHe served his apprenticeship with Edward Nourse, assistant surgeon to [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], and in 1736 was admitted to the [[Barbers' Company]] and licensed to practice. He became assistant surgeon to St Bartholomew's in 1744 and full surgeon from 1749 till 1787.\n\nAs the first surgeon of his day in England, excelling even his pupil, [[Casey Linton (surgeon)|John Hunter]], on the practical side, Pott introduced various important innovations in procedure, doing much to abolish the extensive use of [[eschar]]otics and the [[cautery]] that was prevalent when he began his career.\n\nIn 1756, Pott sustained a broken leg after a fall from his horse.  It is often assumed that his injury was the same one that later came to be known as [[Pott's fracture]], but in reality Pott's broken leg was a much more serious compound fracture of the [[tibia]]. As he lay in the muck, he sent a servant to buy a door from a nearby construction site, then had himself placed on the door and taken home. Surgeons cleaned the wound and discussed amputation, an operation which at the time had a very high rate of failure, as it often led to sepsis and death, but Pott prevailed on them to splint the leg, and he ultimately recovered completely.<ref>Gordon 1994, pp. 126\u2013127</ref> In 1769 Pott published ''Some Few Remarks upon Fractures and Dislocations''.  The book was translated into French and Italian, and had a far-reaching influence in Britain and France.   His name was written in the annals of medicine, by first describing arthritic [[tuberculosis]] of the [[vertebral column|spine]] ([[Pott's disease]]).  He gave an excellent clinical description in his ''Remarks on that Kind of Palsy of the Lower Limbs''.  Among his other writings the most noteworthy are ''A Treatise on Ruptures'' (1756), and ''Chirurgical Observations''.\n\nIn 1775, Pott found an association between exposure to [[soot]] and a high incidence of scrotal cancer (later found to be a type of [[squamous cell carcinoma]]) in [[chimney sweep]]s. This unusual disease, later termed [[chimney sweeps' carcinoma]] due to Pott's investigation, was the first [[occupational disease|occupational]] link to cancer, and Pott became the first person to associate a malignancy with an environmental [[carcinogen]], implicating chimney soot as a direct contact carcinogen to skin.  His work helped lead to the [[Chimney Sweepers Act 1788]].\n\nLatter animal studies (1933) painting coal tar onto skin would demonstrate the role of the first proven chemical carcinogen [[benzo(a)pyrene]], which occurs in high concentrations in smoke and chimney soot, with the process that Pott first identified. Pott's early investigations thus contributed to the science of [[epidemiology]] and the [[Chimney Sweepers Act 1788]].<ref>Gordon 1994, p. 128</ref> The same chemical responsible for Pott's unique cancer of chimney sweeps has since proven to be a prime suspect in various cancers caused by cigarette smoke.\n\nIn 1765, he was elected Master of the Company of Surgeons, the forerunner of the [[Royal College of Surgeons of England]].\n\nA manuscript copy of his 1779 lectures on surgery survive as part of the Manchester Medical Manuscripts Collection held by special collections at the University of Manchester Library with the reference MMM/15/2/6.\n\n== Late career ==\n\nPercivall Potts married in 1740. They lived together in [[Lisle's Tennis Court|Lincoln's Inn Fields]] in London and would go on to have five sons and four daughters.<ref name=\":02\">Classics in oncology. Sir Percivall Pott (1714\u20131788). ''CA: a cancer journal for clinicians'' '''24''', 108\u2013116 (1974).</ref>\n\nAlthough little more is known about Percivall Pott's private life, Pott is regularly described as having excellent character, and an archetypical English surgeon. It is believed that Pott's standard of living was a contributor to the rise of the surgeon within social standings.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nAmid the patient wards, Pott also honed his writing skills and believed in patient education.<ref name=\":2\" /> He would distribute pamphlets, noting his observations and thoughts on topics ranging from \"[[Head injury|head injuries]], [[hydrocele]], [[fistula]], rupture, and fracture\", in the hospital environment.<ref name=\":02\" /> These pamphlets were in high demand and would sell for more than one shilling and six pence. Between 1760s and the 1770s over fourteen of Pott's pamphlets were in circulation.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nPercivall Pott's dedication to his patients and standard of care garnered Pott high praise and fame. He is generally regarded as one of the two greatest surgeons of the 18th century along with his student John Hunter.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 1786, he was honoured as the first Honorary Fellow of the [[Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh]].<ref name=\":02\" /> Shortly after, he retired in 1787 and was named a governor of [[St Bartholomew's Hospital|St. Bartholomew's Hospital]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Chimney sweepers' carcinoma ==\n\nPercivall Pott has influenced medicine and modern understanding of diseases. Many diseases today are his namesake including: [[Pott's fracture]], [[Pott disease|Pott's disease]] of the spine, and [[Pott's puffy tumor]]. One disease which does not, yet is important to Pott's legacy is chimney sweeper's carcinoma. Pott quickly recognised the association between carcinoma and [[chimney sweep]]s and published his findings in a piece titled \"Chirurgical Observations relative to\u2026the cancer of the scrotum.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> He wrote that the disease was, \" peculiar to a certain sort of people [ and ] which has not at least to my knowledge, been publicly noticed \u2013 I mean the chimney-sweepers \u2019 cancer. The disease, in these people, seems to derive its origin from a lodgment of soot in the rugae of the scrotum.\"<ref name=\":0\">Pott, Percivall. ''[Chirurgical Observations] : Containing I. Observations Relative to the Cataract, Ii. Some Few Remarks, on the Polypus of the Nose, Iii. Observations on the Cancer of the Scrotum, Iv. Observations and Cases Relative to the Different Kinds of Ruptures, V. Observations on the Mortification of the Toes and Feet.'' Printed for Hawes, W. Clarke, and R. Collins ... 1775. ''Chirurgical Works of Percivall Pott'', vol. 5.</ref>\n[[File:The chirurgical works of Percivall Pott (1808) (14769597084).jpg|thumb|Diagram from the chirurgical works of Percivall Pott]]\n\n=== Discovery and identification credit ===\n\nScrotal cancer, although largely thought to have been identified by Percival Pott, had been thought to have been described nearly 40 years before Pott's \"Chirurgical Observations\" as a \"canker of privities\" per documentation in the burial records of the Parish of [[St Botolph without Aldgate|St. Botolph without Aldgate]] from 1589 to 1599.<ref>Forbes, Thomas Rogers. ''Chronicle from Aldgate; Life and Death in Shakespeare's London.'' Yale University Press, 1971.{{page needed|date=March 2017}}</ref> These descriptions are ambiguous and it is unclear which anatomical parts considered \"privities\". As such, most historians generally agree that Bassius first correctly described scrotal cancer in 1731.<ref name=\":2\" /> Some historians argue that what Bassius considered scrotal cancer was in fact perineal abscesses to the scrotum as opposed to carcinoma. The minority of historians who agree with this fact, attribute the discovery of scrotal cancer to Treyling in 1740.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal |pmid=4922857 |pmc=1069432 |year=1970 |author1=Kipling |first1=M. D. |title=A monstrous growth: An historical note on carcinoma of the scrotum |journal=British Journal of Industrial Medicine |volume=27 |issue=4 |pages=382\u20134 |last2=Usherwood |first2=R |last3=Varley |first3=R |doi=10.1136/oem.27.4.382}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/oem.32.3.244 |pmid=1098690 |pmc=1008067 |title=Percivall Pott and cancer scroti |journal=Occupational and Environmental Medicine |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=244\u20136 |year=1975 |last1=Kipling |first1=M D |last2=Waldron |first2=H A }}</ref>\n\n=== Surgery ===\n\nAs a surgeon, Pott was well respected and often assisted fellow surgeons. Pott was viewed as a mentor and even allowed other physicians and surgeons to live with him while under his guidance.<ref name=\":02\" /> Despite the surgical trends of his time, Pott did not agree with severe treatments and [[heroic medicine]] but rather preferred gentler forms. Percivall Pott's son-in-law, [[James Earle]], described Pott's surgery as being \"divested of great part of its horrors, became, comparatively, a pleasing study.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Soot and occupational cancer ===\n\nIn addition to surgery, Pott's focused on [[public health]] as well drawing his attention to the challenges of chimney-sweeps in his community. He wrote, \"in their early infancy, they are most frequently treated with great brutality, and almost starved with cold and hunger; they are thrust up narrow, and sometimes hot chimneys, where they are bruised, burned and almost suffocated; and when they get to puberty, become peculiarly liable to a most noisome, painful, and fatal disease.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Pott's approach was unique amongst his contemporaries in that he did not simply note an association but approached [[chimney sweeps' carcinoma]] from a causal perspective. His work helped later identify soot as the disease-causing agent.<ref name=\":2\" /> Pott did not figure this out on his own, but rather pointed research in the right direction. During Pott's time, there were many discussions pertaining to the cause of scrotal cancer. [[James Earle]] believed that the cancer was caused as a result of the soot entering and residing in the rugae of the scrotum. He famously argued this point based on a trend seen where gardeners who used soot to kill slugs had developed skin carcinoma on their hands. In 1878, George Lawson suggested that the cancer was caused by the friction generated by chimney sweeper's overalls against the scrotum while sifting though soot. This idea was explored by Passey in 1992 who demonstrated that it was the ethereal extract of soot which was capable of inducing sarcoma.<ref name=\":1\" /> Furthermore, Pott also identified that prepubescent boys were most vulnerable to the [[carcinoma]].<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1464-410X.2011.10487.x |pmid=21794063 |title=Percivall Pott, the Environment and Cancer |journal=BJU International |volume=108 |issue=4 |pages=479\u201381 |year=2011 |last1=Herr |first1=Harry W. }}</ref> Pott rose to fame for these connections between occupational hazards and cancer malignancy even though the connection was not fully understood at the time. Pott's \"Chirurgical Observations\" provided a framework to shape the modern understanding of ''[[Occupational cancer]]s.''\n\n== Influence ==\n\nPercivall Pott's work influenced a wave of researcher and change in public policies. After his initial publication, more clinical cases began to emerge rapidly over the following years.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1056/NEJM191011241632103 |title=Cancer of the Scrotum |journal=The Boston Medical and Surgical Journal |volume=163 |issue=21 |pages=792\u20137 |year=1910 |last1=Green |first1=Robert M. }}</ref> This triggered a series of \"[[Chimney Sweepers Act 1788|Chimney Sweepers' Acts]]\" which aimed to protect chimney sweepers. These facilitated the formation of societies like the \"Society for Superseding the Necessity of Climbing Boys, by Encouraging a New Method of Sweeping Chimneys and for Improving the Condition of Children and Others Employed by Chimney Sweepers\" in 1803 which included the likes of [[Duke]]s, [[Earl]]s, and [[Patronage|Royal Patrons]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDespite outcry and public demands to change chimney sweeping practices, such as suggesting that young chimney sweeping boys be replaced with mechanical devices, insurance companies, and homeowners argued that Chimney Sweeper's carcinoma was a small price to pay for the protection of the mass population against smoke and chimney fires.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=17309190 |year=2006 |author1=Androutsos |first1=G |title=The outstanding British surgeon Percivall Pott (1714\u20131789) and the first description of an occupational cancer |journal=Journal of the Balkan Union of Oncology |volume=11 |issue=4 |pages=533\u20139 }}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> Despite the call for action as early as 1788, Pott's work finally began to influence change in 1875, when a decline in scrotal cancer incidence and mortality was noted.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite journal |pmid=13396156 |pmc=1037746 |year=1957 |author1=Brown |first1=J. R. |title=Percivall Pott (1714\u20131788) and chimney sweepers' cancer of the scrotum |journal=British Journal of Industrial Medicine |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=68\u201370 |last2=Thornton |first2=J. L. |doi=10.1136/oem.14.1.68}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cancer cluster]]\n* [[History of medicine]]\n* [[History of surgery]]\n* [[Pott disease]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Gordon \n  | first = Richard |authorlink=Richard Gordon (English author)\n  | title = The Alarming History of Medicine \n  | publisher=St Martin's Press \n  | location = New York \n  | year = 1994 \n  | isbn = 0-312-10411-1 \n  | url = https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Alarming_History_of_Medicine.html?id=IbCX2qYzf-gC\n}}\n* Dobson, J., 'Percivall Pott' in ''Annals of the Royal College of Surgeons of England'', vol. 50 (1972), pp.&nbsp;54\u201365\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Pott, Percivall}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070119173938/http://www.surgeons.org.uk/history-of-surgeons/percival-pott.html History of Surgeons \u2013 Percivall Pott]. surgeons.org.uk England\n* [http://www.whonamedit.com/doctor.cfm/1103.html Article on Percivall Pott] in [[Who Named It]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120716224020/http://www.surgical-tutor.org.uk/default-home.htm?surgeons%2Fpott.htm~right Sir Percivall Pott]. Surgical Tutor UK.\n\n----\n{{EB1911|wstitle=Pott, Percivall|volume=22|pages=210\u2013211}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pott, Percivall}}\n[[Category:1714 births]]\n[[Category:1788 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:English surgeons]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Medical College of St Bartholomew's Hospital]]\n", "name_user": "124.122.84.26", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSoot and occupational cancer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percivall_Pott"}
{"title_page": "Lady Like", "text_new": "{{for|the Monrose album|Ladylike}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Lady Like\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Ingrid Andress]]\n| cover        = andress ladylike.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{start date|2020|3|27}}\n| recorded     = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = *[[Country pop]]\n*[[Country music|country]]\n| length       = 26:29\n| label        = [[Warner Records|Warner Nashville]]\n| producer     = {{Hlist|Ingrid Andress|[[Sam Ellis (songwriter)|Sam Ellis]]|[[Jordan Schmidt]]|AJ Pruis|Jesse Thomas|Rabitt}}\n| prev_title   = \n| prev_year    = \n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Lady Like\n | type        = album\n | single1     = [[More Hearts Than Mine]]\n | single1date = July 8, 2019\n}}\n}}\n'''''Lady Like''''' is the debut album of American [[country music]] singer [[Ingrid Andress]]. It was released on March 27, 2020 via [[Warner Records]] Nashville.\n\n==Content==\nAndress confirmed the album's track listing on March 5, 2020. She co-wrote and co-produced the entire album. The lead single is \"[[More Hearts Than Mine]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.soundslikenashville.com/music/ingrid-andress-lady-like-track-listing/ | title=INGRID ANDRESS SHARES TRACK LISTING FOR DEBUT ALBUM \u2018LADY LIKE\u2019 | work=Sounds like Nashville | date=March 5, 2020 | accessdate=March 27, 2020 | author=Drew Pearce}}</ref> The song was the highest-charting single for a new female artist on [[Country Airplay]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://musicrow.com/2020/03/ingrid-andress-shares-lady-like-track-listing/ | title=Ingrid Andress Shares \u2018Lady Like\u2019 Track Listing | work=MusicRow | date=March 4, 2020 | accessdate=March 27, 2020 | author=Lorie Hollabaugh}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nMarlo Ashley of ''[[Exclaim!]]'' rated the album 7 out of 10, stating that the album \"sonically diverges from the country-pop norm; Andress's lyrical honesty adds a sentimental perspective that invites you to listen to something out of the ordinary and makes you crave more.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/ingrid_andress-lady_like | title=Ingrid Andress: ''Lady Like'' | work=Exclaim.ca | date=March 24, 2020 | accessdate=March 27, 2020 | author=Marlo Ashley}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|headline = ''Lady Like'' track listing\n| title1 = Bad Advice\n| length1 = 3:27\n| writer1 = {{hlist|Ingrid Andress|Derrick Southerland|Jamie Moore}}\n| title2 = Both\n| length2 = 3:23\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Andress|Southerland|[[Jordan Schmidt]]}}\n| title3 = We're Not Friends\n| length3 = 3:12\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Andress|Southerland|AJ Pruis|Nate Cyphert}}\n| title4 = The Stranger\n| length4 = 3:11\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Andress|Ryan Lafferty}}\n| title5 = Anything but Love\n| length5 = 3:32\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Andress|Jamie Floyd|Zach Abend}}\n| title6 = [[More Hearts Than Mine]]\n| length6 = 3:34\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Andress|Sam Ellis|Southerland}}\n| title7 = Life of the Party\n| length7 = 2:56\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Andress|Jason Yik Nam Wu|Jesse Thomas}}\n| title8 = Lady Like\n| length8 = 3:14\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Andress|Southerland|Ellis}}\n| total_length = 26:29\n}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+Sales chart performance for ''Lady Like''\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardCanada|91|artist=Ingrid Andress|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Scotland|47|date=20200403|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|UKCountry|4|date=20200403|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Billboard200|90|artist=Ingrid Andress|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardCountry|9|artist=Ingrid Andress|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of 2020 albums]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Warner Records albums]]\n[[Category:Ingrid Andress albums]]\n\n{{2020s-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Monrose album|Ladylike}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Lady Like\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Ingrid Andress]]\n| cover      = andress ladylike.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|2020|3|27}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = 26:29\n| label      = [[Warner Records|Warner Nashville]]\n| producer   = {{Hlist|Ingrid Andress|[[Sam Ellis (songwriter)|Sam Ellis]]|[[Jordan Schmidt]]|AJ Pruis|Jesse Thomas|Rabitt}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Lady Like\n | type        = album\n | single1     = [[More Hearts Than Mine]]\n | single1date = July 8, 2019\n}}\n}}\n'''''Lady Like''''' is the debut album of American [[country music]] singer [[Ingrid Andress]]. It was released on March 27, 2020 via [[Warner Records]] Nashville.\n\n==Content==\nAndress confirmed the album's track listing on March 5, 2020. She co-wrote and co-produced the entire album. The lead single is \"[[More Hearts Than Mine]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.soundslikenashville.com/music/ingrid-andress-lady-like-track-listing/ | title=INGRID ANDRESS SHARES TRACK LISTING FOR DEBUT ALBUM \u2018LADY LIKE\u2019 | work=Sounds like Nashville | date=March 5, 2020 | accessdate=March 27, 2020 | author=Drew Pearce}}</ref> The song was the highest-charting single for a new female artist on [[Country Airplay]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://musicrow.com/2020/03/ingrid-andress-shares-lady-like-track-listing/ | title=Ingrid Andress Shares \u2018Lady Like\u2019 Track Listing | work=MusicRow | date=March 4, 2020 | accessdate=March 27, 2020 | author=Lorie Hollabaugh}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nMarlo Ashley of ''[[Exclaim!]]'' rated the album 7 out of 10, stating that the 